  "An employer-sponsored retirement savings plan that allows pre-tax or Roth contributions with potential employer matching": "",
  "A 401(k) is an employer-sponsored defined-contribution retirement plan. Employees contribute a portion of their salary, often with employer matching, and investments grow tax-advantaged until withdrawal.": "",
  "What is the key tax difference between Traditional and Roth retirement accounts?": "",
  "Traditional contributions are taxed now; Roth contributions are taxed later": "",
  "Traditional contributions are pre-tax (taxed at withdrawal); Roth contributions are after-tax (tax-free at withdrawal)": "",
  "Both are taxed identically": "",
  "Roth accounts have no contribution limits": "",
  "Traditional: tax deduction now, taxed on withdrawal. Roth: no deduction now, but withdrawals are completely tax-free. The choice depends on whether you expect higher or lower tax rates in retirement.": "",
  "What does 'tax-deferred growth' mean?": "",
  "Investment gains are not taxed each year but are taxed when withdrawn, allowing the full amount to compound": "",
  "Only dividends are taxed; capital gains are exempt": "",
  "The government delays collecting any taxes indefinitely": "",
  "You never pay taxes on the growth": "",
  "Tax-deferred growth means you do not pay capital gains or income tax on annual returns within the account. The entire balance compounds, and taxes are paid only upon withdrawal — a significant advantage over taxable accounts.": "",
