  "A homeowner has a $200,000 mortgage at 7% for 30 years (PMT ≈ $1,331). After 5 years, they refinance the remaining $190,000 at 5% for 25 years (new PMT ≈ $1,110). How much do they save per month?": "",
  "~$500/month": "",
  "~$221/month": "",
  "~$50/month": "",
  "~$100/month": "",
  "Monthly savings = $1,331 - $1,110 = $221/month or $2,652/year. Refinancing to a lower rate can produce significant savings, but closing costs should be factored in to determine the break-even period.": "",
  "Investor A puts $10,000 in a lump sum at 8% for 20 years. Investor B saves $500/year at 8% for 20 years. Who has more at the end?": "",
  "Investor A with ~$46,610": "",
  "They are equal at $20,000": "",
  "Investor B with ~$46,610": "",
  "Investor B with ~$22,881": "",
  "Investor A: $10,000 × 1.08^20 = $46,610. Investor B: $500 × [(1.08^20 - 1)/0.08] = $500 × 45.76 = $22,881. A lump sum invested early benefits from compounding on the full amount from day one.": "",
  "A couple needs $80,000/year in retirement income. Social Security will provide $30,000/year. Using the 4% withdrawal rule, how much must they save in their retirement portfolio to cover the gap?": "",
  "$800,000": "",
  "$500,000": "",
  "$1,250,000": "",
  "Savings gap = $80,000 - $30,000 = $50,000/year needed from portfolio. At 4% rule: $50,000 / 0.04 = $1,250,000 required portfolio. This demonstrates why calculating the gap between desired income and guaranteed income is critical.": "",
  "AP multi-step problem: An employee earns $70,000, contributes 10% to a Traditional 401(k), and receives a 50% employer match up to 6%. What is the total annual amount going into their retirement account?": "",
  "$7,000": "",
  "$9,100": "",
  "$10,500": "",
  "$7,700": "",
  "Employee contributes 10% × $70,000 = $7,000. Employer matches 50% up to 6% of salary: 50% × (6% × $70,000) = 50% × $4,200 = $2,100. Total = $7,000 + $2,100 = $9,100/year going into the account.": ""
